<h2>Finding 1 — delta <em>type</em> and delta <em>disposition</em> are orthogonal (load-bearing)</h2>
<p>
  reg-suit's <code>new / changed / deleted</code> is a <strong>structural type</strong> (what changed about the
  region's existence); Chromatic/Percy's <code>accept / deny</code> is a <strong>review disposition</strong>
  (the verdict on the change). Every tool that has both keeps them on <strong>separate axes</strong>. Folding
  them into one flat enum reproduces the orthogonality break WE already ruled against for <code>action.level</code>
  (<a href="/backlog/1318-action-intent-emphasis-style-axis-fill-outline-ghost-link-or/">#1318</a>/<a href="/backlog/1324-revisit-whether-action-level-models-outcome-role-continue-ca/">#1324</a>)
  and for <a href="/intents/progress/">progress</a> (<a href="/backlog/2533-console-board-derived-ui-standards/">#2533</a> Fork 2 — provenance kept off completion).
</p>

<h2>Finding 2 — anchoring splits pixel vs structural</h2>
<p>
  Along the <em>"are the two panes pixel-aligned?"</em> line. Visual-regression (baseline vs a new capture of
  the <em>same</em> view) is pixel-aligned, so a <strong>bounding box</strong> locates a region. Design-vs-built,
  Figma, and PR-diff panes are <strong>not</strong> pixel-aligned (different renderers, layouts, sizes), so they
  anchor <strong>structurally</strong> (a DOM selector / layer node-id / line range). The board's
  <em>design → built</em> case is the structural kind; a whole-pattern contract must carry <strong>both</strong>,
  tagged — a pixel box degrades to noise under a layout shift, and a structural anchor needs a correspondence the
  two renders may not share.
</p>

<h2>Finding 3 — the board surfaced a third disposition no incumbent first-classes</h2>
<p>
  <strong><em>"expected, not reached yet"</em></strong> — known drift that is neither an accept nor a reject.
  First-classing it as a distinct disposition (alongside accepted/rejected/unreviewed) is the novel contribution
  the console board surfaced.
</p>

<h2>Finding 4 — a producer/consumer split mirrors Web Graph's two seams</h2>
<p>
  The tools split cleanly into a <strong>differ</strong> (turns two renders into typed delta regions —
  pixelmatch, odiff, reg-cli) and a <strong>review surface</strong> (renders + dispositions them), just as
  <a href="/projects/webgraph/">Web Graph</a> splits <code>CustomGraphLayout</code> (invents positions) from
  <code>CustomGraphRenderer</code> (draws). The likely end-state is a <code>visual-diff</code> <strong>intent</strong>
  (the review-surface UX contract) plus a swappable <strong>differ protocol</strong> — but <strong>this decision
  should mint the intent and only <em>name</em> the differ seam as a follow-on</strong>, since shaping the
  review-surface contract is what Fork 5 asked for.
</p>

<h2>The shaped contract</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Delta-type taxonomy (two orthogonal axes):</strong> a structural <code>type</code>
    (<code>added | removed | changed</code>) × a review <code>disposition</code>
    (<code>unreviewed | accepted | rejected | expected</code>).</li>
  <li><strong>Anchor payload (tagged union):</strong> <code>anchorType: 'pixel-region' | 'dom-selector' |
    'node-id' | 'line-range'</code>, carrying <code>box?</code> for the pixel case and <code>ref?</code> for the
    structural cases, plus the two pane references being compared.</li>
  <li><strong>Accept / typed-region model:</strong> a <strong>per-region disposition</strong> that promotes the
    built state into the baseline on <code>accepted</code>, first-classes <code>expected</code>, may be scoped by
    type, with the whole-surface approve composed <em>above</em> it (never a substitute for it).</li>
</ul>

<h2>Recommendation</h2>
<p>
  <strong>MINT a <code>visual-diff</code> intent</strong> on the shaped contract — distinct from
  <a href="/intents/audit-timeline/">audit-timeline</a> (temporal feed), composing Web Graph's two-seam precedent
  for the eventual differ protocol. The pattern is dispositive prior art; the contract is now shaped; the honest
  verdict is <strong>mint</strong> (not park, not mint-blind). The remaining judgment for the ratification turn is
  scoped to the five forks recorded in <a href="/backlog/2538-shape-the-annotated-visual-diff-surface-contract-then-decide-mint/">#2538</a>.
  Full grounding: <code>we:reports/2026-07-18-annotated-visual-diff-surface.md</code>.
</p>
